So, we've got the steps in deciphering the
pictures,

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:13.060
Let's look at out original picture again and
see if we can make sense of it.

00:02:13.580 --> 00:02:19.100
OK, well this very faint circle here is just
an electron kicked out of an atom.

00:02:19.100 --> 00:02:22.640
Like the first part of our three pieces of
the jigsaw puzzle.

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:27.660
At this point here we see a whole series of
negatively charged particles

00:02:27.660 --> 00:02:32.480
curving off that way, and positives curving
off the other way.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:38.820
Then there's a gap where something without
any charge at all must have gone

00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:44.840
And it reveals its presence when it turns
into two particles that do reveal themselves.

00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:48.800
So, that shows you how you begin to decipher
the picture.

00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:53.940
But in this picture there's something very
interesting. This gap here.

00:02:54.280 --> 00:02:57.720
A particle without any charge must have lived

00:02:57.720 --> 00:02:59.820
and for a very, very short time.

00:03:00.020 --> 00:03:01.180
Let me show you what I mean.

00:03:03.140 --> 00:03:05.100
I've got this little clock along the bottom.

00:03:05.520 --> 00:03:09.260
This is the spot where this neutral object
was created.

00:03:09.260 --> 00:03:10.560
And that's where it died.

00:03:10.560 --> 00:03:12.080
Now what's this clock doing?

00:03:12.380 --> 00:03:15.380
Let's just think what happens in this thing
here.

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:18.640
We've got this bubble chamber and the camera
taking photographs.

00:03:18.640 --> 00:03:21.550
There's particles shooting in from one side,
almost at the speed of light.

00:03:21.700 --> 00:03:23.340
They are across the bubble chamber in a flash.

00:03:24.580 --> 00:03:28.640
But the camera takes the picture, it's probably
for a thousanth of a second.

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:30.420
Which is a short time to you and me,

00:03:30.420 --> 00:03:33.800
but it's a long time to a particle that is
moving near the speed of light.

00:03:34.760 --> 00:03:39.500
It's as if the particle enters this side of
the bubble chamber and the clock starts.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.700
By the time it's got to here, the clock is
just passed the starting point.

00:03:44.940 --> 00:03:47.740
By the time it's got to here, it's a millionth
of a second later.

00:03:47.740 --> 00:03:51.040
By the time it's got to here it's four millionths
of a second later

00:03:51.040 --> 00:03:52.560
and then it exits on the other side.

00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:55.020
But the camera shutter has been open all the
time.

00:03:56.360 --> 00:04:00.200
And it takes what appears to be a still photograph
as you see here.

00:04:00.200 --> 00:04:01.560
But in fact it's a timelapse.

00:04:01.960 --> 00:04:04.160
The time is running from one side to the other.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:10.260
So between here and here it's maybe a millionth
of a second or less.

00:04:11.280 --> 00:04:16.040
So this picture has captured the passage,
the life and death of a particle,

00:04:16.680 --> 00:04:18.940
that lives for less than a millionth of a
second.

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:22.999
It's astonishing to think that with this simple
device

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.120
you can capture short, short timescales and
make them for real.

00:04:26.840 --> 00:04:30.440
And that is as important a part of the universe
as everything else.

